Question 1

Prove that if the simple correlation between y and x is negative, the slope of regressing y on x will also be negative.

Definitions

  • Correlation: \(\rho(x,y) = \frac{\text{cov}(x,y)}{\sqrt{\text{var}(x)}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}}\).
  • Slope: \(\beta = \frac{\text{cov}(x,y)}{\text{var}(x)}\).

Assumptions

  • \(\rho(x,y) < 0\).
  • \(\text{var(x)} > 0\).
  • \(\text{var(y)} > 0\).

Question 1

Prove that if the simple correlation between y and x is negative, the slope of regressing y on x will also be negative.

Goal

  • \(\beta < 0\).

Proof

Let \(\rho(x,y) < 0\). Then,

\[ \begin{align*} \rho(x,y) &< 0 \\ \frac{\text{cov}(x,y)}{\sqrt{\text{var}(x)}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}} &< 0 \end{align*} \]

Question 1

Prove that if the simple correlation between y and x is negative, the slope of regressing y on x will also be negative.

Proof

\[ \begin{align*} \frac{\text{cov}(x,y)}{\sqrt{\text{var}(x)}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}} \cdot \underbrace{\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}}_{+} &< 0 \cdot \underbrace{\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}}_{+} \\ \frac{\text{cov}(x,y)}{\sqrt{\text{var}(x)}} \cdot \underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{\text{var}(x)}}}_{+} &< 0 \cdot \underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{\text{var}(x)}}}_{+} \\ \beta = \rho \cdot \frac{\sigma_{y}}{\sigma_{x}} = \frac{\text{cov}(x,y)}{\text{var}(x)} &< 0. \end{align*} \]

Question 2

While the error terms and the OLS residuals are clearly not the same thing, it is always the case that \(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \epsilon_{i} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \hat{\epsilon}_{i} = 0\) Discuss.

Assumptions

  • Linear regression model:
    • Variables:
      • Dependent: \(Y_{i}\).
      • Independent: \((1, X_{1i})\).
    • \(Y_{i} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} X_{1i} + e_{i}, \; \forall i\).
    • \(\mathbb{E}[e|X] = 0\).

Question 2

While the error terms and the OLS residuals are clearly not the same thing, it is always the case that \(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \epsilon_{i} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \hat{\epsilon}_{i} = 0\) Discuss.

Assumptions

  • Ordinary Least Squares estimator:
    • \((\hat{\beta}_{0}, \hat{\beta}_{1}) = \arg\min_{(b_{0}, b_{1})} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (Y_{i} - b_{0} \cdot 1 - b_{1} \cdot X_{1i})^2\).
    • \(Y_{i} = X_{i}' \hat{\beta} + \hat{\epsilon}_{i} = \hat{Y}_{i} + \hat{\epsilon}_{i}\).

Goal

  1. \(\sum_{i=1}^{n} e_{i} \; ? \; 0\).
  2. \(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \hat{\epsilon}_{i} \; ? \; 0\).

Question 2

While the error terms and the OLS residuals are clearly not the same thing, it is always the case that \(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \epsilon_{i} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \hat{\epsilon}_{i} = 0\) Discuss.

Goal 1.

No.Â This property only holds in expectation. From the assumptions, we know \(\mathbb{E}[e|X] = 0\). Then, we apply the Law of Iterated Expectations: \[\mathbb{E}[\mathbb{E}[e|X]] = \mathbb{E}[0]\] \[\mathbb{E}[e] = 0. \]

  • If you donât know the Law of Iterated Expectations, you had it as Assumption 4 on the Lecture Slides.
  • Another way of thinking about it is that if it holds for each \(X\), it must hold in general/unconditionally.

Question 2

While the error terms and the OLS residuals are clearly not the same thing, it is always the case that \(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \epsilon_{i} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \hat{\epsilon}_{i} = 0\) Discuss.

Goal 2.

Yes, this property always holds. It is a property of the OLS estimator.

  • First-order condition: \(-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}Y_{i} + 2\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}X_{i}'\hat{\beta} = 0\).
  • Simplify the 2âs and substitute the model: \(-\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}X_{i}'\hat{\beta} + \sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}X_{i}'\hat{\beta} + \sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}\hat{\epsilon}_{i} = 0\).
  • Consider the case for the variable 1: \(\sum_{i=1}^{n}1\cdot\hat{\epsilon}_{i} = 0\).

Question 3a

Which of the following two statements do you agree with, and why:

  1. The existence of this sample categorically proves that our hypothesis on the population relation is wrong.
  2. The existence of this sample suggests (but does not prove) that our hypothesis on the population relation is wrong.

Question 3a

Which of the following two statements do you agree with, and why:

  1. The existence of this sample categorically proves that our hypothesis on the population relation is wrong.
  2. The existence of this sample suggests (but does not prove) that our hypothesis on the population relation is wrong.

The proposed population relation underestimates the magnitude of the slope compared to the realised sample. However, remember that we do not know the true population parameter. There is always a chance that we get a non-representative sample. Hence, we need to do hypothesis testing to reject or do not reject the proposed model considering the data we observe.

  2. It is quite likely (but not certain) that the trainee has made a mistake.

Question 3b

Which of the following two statements do you agree with, and why:

  1. Without any doubt, the trainee has made a mistake when handling the data.
  2. It is quite likely (but not certain) that the trainee has made a mistake.

All the residuals are positive. By construction, the sum of residual should be zero. The trainee has made a mistake when handling the data.

Question 4

Derive the OLS estimators.

Ordinary Least Squares estimator

At this level, I do not have an alternative solution to the undergraduate textbook. \[\hat{\beta} = \arg\min_{b} (\mathbf{Y} - \mathbf{X} \cdot b)^2\]

The least squares estimator is: \[\hat{\beta} = (\mathbf{X}'\mathbf{X})^{-1}\mathbf{X}'\mathbf{Y}. \]

This is the multivariate version of the simple linear regression model: the estimated covariance between \(X\) and \(Y\) divided by the variance of \(X\).

Question 5

Write down the formula for the simple correlation between \(y\) and \(\hat{y}\). Show that this simple correlation is equal to the square root of \(R^{2}\).

Definitions

  • Correlation: \(\rho(y, \hat{y}) = \frac{\text{cov}(y,\hat{y})}{\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(\hat{y})}}\).
  • \(y_{i} = \hat{y}_{i} + \hat{\epsilon}_{i}\).
  • \(R^2 = \frac{\text{var}(\hat{y})}{\text{var}(y)}\).

Goal

\[\rho(y, \hat{y}) = \sqrt{R^{2}}\]

Question 5

Write down the formula for the simple correlation between \(y\) and \(\hat{y}\). Show that this simple correlation is equal to the square root of \(R^{2}\).

Proof

First, we calculate the variance of \(y\). The covariance between \(\hat{y}\) and \(\hat{\epsilon}\) is zero due to the mechanical properties of OLS.

\[ \begin{align*} \text{var}(y) &= \text{var}(\hat{y} + \hat{\epsilon}) \\ &= \text{var}(\hat{y}) + \text{var}(\hat{\epsilon}) + 2\cdot\underbrace{\text{cov}(\hat{y}, \hat{\epsilon})}_{0} \\ &= \text{var}(\hat{y}) + \text{var}(\hat{\epsilon}) \end{align*} \]

Question 5

Write down the formula for the simple correlation between \(y\) and \(\hat{y}\). Show that this simple correlation is equal to the square root of \(R^{2}\).

Proof

Then, \[ \begin{align*} \rho(y, \hat{y}) &= \frac{\text{cov}(y, \hat{y})}{\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(\hat{y})}} \\ &= \frac{\text{cov}(\hat{y} + \hat{\epsilon}, \hat{y})}{\sqrt{\text{var}(\hat{y} + \hat{\epsilon})}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(\hat{y})}} \\ &= \frac{\overbrace{\text{cov}(\hat{y},\hat{y})}^{\text{var}(\hat{y})} + \overbrace{\text{cov}(\hat{\epsilon}, \hat{y})}^{0}}{\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(\hat{y})}} \end{align*} \]

Question 5

Write down the formula for the simple correlation between \(y\) and \(\hat{y}\). Show that this simple correlation is equal to the square root of \(R^{2}\).

Proof

Then, \[ \begin{align*} \rho(y, \hat{y}) &= \frac{\text{var}(\hat{y})}{\sqrt{\text{var}(y)}\cdot\sqrt{\text{var}(\hat{y})}} \\ &= \sqrt{\frac{\text{var}(\hat{y})}{\text{var}(y)}} \\ &= \sqrt{R^{2}}= \sqrt{\frac{1}{1 + \frac{\text{var}(\hat{\epsilon})}{\text{var}(\hat{y})}}} \end{align*} \]

Question 6

Whatâs an estimator?

Question 6

Whatâs an estimator?

Estimator: Statistic (function of the data) to infer the value of an unknown parameter.

From the population to the sample, we have:

  • Estimand: \(Y_{i} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} x_{i} + e_{i}\)
  • Estimator: \(\hat{\beta}_{1} = \frac{\text{cov}(y_{i}, x_{i})}{\text{var}(x_{i})}.\)
  • Estimate: \(\hat{\beta}_{1} = 0.5\).

Question 6

Properties of estimators

  1. Unbiasedness: \(\mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta} - \beta] = 0\). âRight on averageâ.
  2. Consistency: \(\hat{\beta} \xrightarrow{p} \beta\). As our sample size increases, the probability that our estimator is far away from the true parameter goes to zero.
  3. Efficiency: \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta})\) is the smallest possible.

Question 7

\(\uparrow \text{var}(x) \implies \downarrow \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{i})\)

Definitions

  • Variance of the estimator:
    • \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{n \sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i} - \bar{x})^2} = \frac{\sigma^{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{n (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\).
    • \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i} - \bar{x})^2}\).
  • Sample variance of the independent variable:
    • \(\hat{\text{var}(x)} = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2} - \frac{n}{n-1}\bar{x}^{2}\)
    • \(\implies (n - 1)\cdot \hat{\text{var}}(x) + n\cdot \bar{x}^{2} = \sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\)

Question 7

\(\uparrow \text{var}(x) \implies \downarrow \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{i})\)

Goal

  • \(\downarrow \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{i})\)

Proof

First, consider \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0})\). \[ \begin{align*} \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) &= \frac{\sigma^{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{n (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})} \\ &= \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \frac{(n - 1)\cdot\hat{\text{var}}(x) + n\bar{x}^{2}}{(n - 1)\hat{\text{var}}(x)} \end{align*} \]

Question 7

\(\uparrow \text{var}(x) \implies \downarrow \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{i})\)

Proof

First, consider \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0})\). \[\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \left(1 + \frac{n\bar{x}^{2}}{(n - 1)\hat{\text{var}}(x)\uparrow}\right) \downarrow \]

Question 7

\(\uparrow \text{var}(x) \implies \downarrow \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{i})\)

Proof

Then, consider \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1})\). \[ \begin{align*} \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1}) &= \frac{\sigma^{2}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2}} \\ &= \frac{\sigma^{2}}{(n - 1)\cdot \hat{\text{var}}(x) \uparrow} \downarrow \end{align*} \]

Question 9

What if we minimise the absolute deviations rather than the squared deviations?

  • Due to the Gauss-Markov theorem, we know the OLS estimator is the best linear unbiased estimator for the homoskedastic linear regression model.
  • There are other linear unbiased estimator, but, they are not as efficient.
  • If we minimise the absolute deviations, we would be modelling the median.

\[\text{Median[Y|X]} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}X_{i}\]

Question 10

\(\mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta}_{1} - \beta_{1}] = 0 \implies \mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta}_{0} - \beta_{0}] = 0\)

Previous results

  • \(\bar{y} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}\bar{x} + \bar{e}\).
  • \(\bar{y} = \hat{\beta}_{0} + \hat{\beta}_{1}\bar{x}\).

Proof

\[ \begin{align*} \mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta}_{0} - \beta_{0}] &= \mathbb{E}[\bar{y} - \hat{\beta}_{1}\bar{x} - \beta_{0}] \\ &= \mathbb{E}[\beta_{0} + \beta_{1}\bar{x} + \bar{e} - \hat{\beta}_{1}\bar{x} -\beta_{0}] \\ &= \mathbb{E}[\beta_{1}\bar{x} + \bar{e} - \hat{\beta}_{1}\bar{x}] \end{align*} \]

Question 10

\(\mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta}_{1} - \beta_{1}] = 0 \implies \mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta}_{0} - \beta_{0}] = 0\)

Proof

\[ \begin{align*} \mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta}_{0} - \beta_{0}] &= \underbrace{\mathbb{E}[\bar{e}]}_{0} - \mathbb{E}[(\hat{\beta}_{1} - \beta_{1})\bar{x}] \\ &= - \underbrace{\mathbb{E}[(\hat{\beta}_{1} - \beta_{1})]}_{0}\bar{x} \\ &= 0 \end{align*} \]

Question 11

\(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \text{var}(\bar{\hat{\epsilon}}_{i}) + \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1} \bar{x}) \implies \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{n (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\)

Previous results

  • \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n \text{var}(x)}\).

Proof

Divide and conquer. First, \(\text{var}(\bar{\hat{\epsilon}}_{i})\). \[\text{var}(\bar{\hat{\epsilon}}_{i}) = \text{var}(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{\epsilon}_{i}) = \frac{1}{n^{2}}\sum_{i=1}^{n} \text{var}(\hat{\epsilon}_{i}) = \frac{n}{n^{2}}\sigma^{2} = \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}\]

Question 11

\(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \text{var}(\bar{\hat{\epsilon}}_{i}) + \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1} \bar{x}) \implies \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{n (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\)

Proof

Then, \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1} \bar{x})\).

\[ \begin{align*} \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1} \bar{x}) &= \bar{x}^{2} \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1}) \\ &= \bar{x}^{2} \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n \text{var}(x)} \\ &= \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \frac{\bar{x}^{2}}{\text{var}(x)} \end{align*} \]

Question 11

\(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \text{var}(\bar{\hat{\epsilon}}_{i}) + \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1} \bar{x}) \implies \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{n (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\)

Proof

Finally, \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0})\). \[ \begin{align*} \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) &= \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \frac{\bar{x}^{2}}{\text{var}(x)} + \frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \\ &=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \left(1 + \frac{\bar{x}^{2}}{\text{var}(x)}\right) \\ &=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \left(1 + \frac{\bar{x}^{2}}{\frac{1}{n} (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\right) \end{align*} \]

Question 11

\(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \text{var}(\bar{\hat{\epsilon}}_{i}) + \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1} \bar{x}) \implies \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \frac{\sigma^{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{n (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\)

Proof

Finally, \(\text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0})\). \[ \begin{align*} \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{0}) &=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \left(1 + \frac{\bar{x}^{2}}{\frac{1}{n} (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\right) \\ &=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \left(\frac{\frac{1}{n} (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2)- \bar{x}^{2} + \bar{x}^{2}}{\frac{1}{n} (\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2})}\right) \\ &=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \cdot \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^2-n\bar{x}^{2}} \end{align*} \]

Question 13

Predict out of sample. \((x_{i}^{*} - \bar{x})^{2}\uparrow \implies \text{var}(\hat{y}_{i}^{*}) \uparrow\)

Definitions

  • Out-of-sample prediction: \(\hat{y}_{i}^{*} = \hat{\beta}_{0} + \hat{\beta}_{1}x_{i}^{*}\).

Previous results

  • \(\bar{y} = \hat{\beta}_{0} + \hat{\beta}_{1}\bar{x}\)

Question 13

Predict out of sample. \((x_{i}^{*} - \bar{x})^{2}\uparrow \implies \text{var}(\hat{y}_{i}^{*}) \uparrow\)

Proof

\[ \begin{align*} \hat{y}_{i}^{*} - \bar{y} &= \hat{\beta}_{1} (x_{i}^{*} - \bar{x}) \\ \text{var}(\hat{y}_{i}^{*} - \bar{y}) &= \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1} (x_{i}^{*} - \bar{x})) \\ \text{var}(\hat{y}_{i}^{*}) &= (x_{i}^{*} - \bar{x})^{2} \text{var}(\hat{\beta}_{1}) \end{align*} \]
